  "topic": "Stablecoin supply over time",
  "summary": "Stablecoin total supply (circulating market cap) grew from roughly $4B at end-2019 to an all-time high of ~$321B in May 2026, per DefiLlama. Growth came in waves: a ~6x surge in 2020-2021 (DeFi/bull market) to ~$163B, a contraction in 2022-2023 (Terra/UST collapse, FTX, BUSD wind-down) bottoming near ~$124-130B, then a strong recovery through 2024-2026 driven by US regulatory clarity (GENIUS Act era), tokenized treasuries, and new entrants. As of 2026-06-16 the total stood at ~$313.5B (USD-pegged). The market is highly concentrated: Tether's USDT (~$186B, ~59% share) and Circle's USDC (~$75B, ~24% share) together hold ~83-85% of supply. Sky's USDS+DAI (~$12.6B combined), Ethena's USDe (volatile, ~$4.5B currently after peaking ~$14.8B in Oct 2025), and newcomers like World Liberty Financial's USD1 (~$4.5B) round out the top tier. Stablecoins represent roughly 9-13% of total crypto market cap. On-chain transfer volume (adjusted/organic, Artemis) rose from ~$1.3T in 2020 to ~$18.4T in 2024, exceeding Visa and Mastercard's individual annual volumes; true payment volume (excluding bots/trading) was ~$390B in 2025 per Artemis/McKinsey. All market-cap series unit = USD billions. Primary source: DefiLlama Stablecoins API (stablecoins.llama.fi), accessed 2026-06-17.",
